        Converts the string into an int using parseInt().

Line 5:         System.out.println("String value: " + text);
        Prints the original string.

Line 6:         System.out.println("Integer value: " + number);
        Prints the converted integer value.

Line 7:     }
        Ends the main method.

Line 8: }
        Ends the class.

Output:
String value: 123
Integer value: 123

Summary:
This program shows how parseInt() converts a string containing digits into an integer.

6. Example Program 2: Read input from user and convert it
Program Headline:
Using parseInt() to convert user input into a number

Why this program is used:
This program shows how parseInt() is very useful when taking input from a user.

Program:
import java.util.Scanner;

public class ParseIntExample2 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);      // Step 1: create Scanner object
        System.out.println("Enter a number:");
        String input = sc.nextLine();             // Step 2: read input as string
        int number = Integer.parseInt(input);     // Step 3: convert string to int

        System.out.println("You entered: " + number);
        System.out.println("Number + 5 = " + (number + 5));

        sc.close();
    }
}

Line-by-line explanation:
Line 1: import java.util.Scanner;
        Imports the Scanner class to read input.

Line 3: public class ParseIntExample2 {
        Declares the class.

Line 4:     public static void main(String[] args) {
        Declares the main method.

Line 5:         Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        Creates an object to read input from the keyboard.

Line 6:         System.out.println("Enter a number:");
        Prompts the user to enter a number.

Line 7:         String input = sc.nextLine();
        Reads the value as a string.

Line 8:         int number = Integer.parseInt(input);
        Converts the input string into an integer.

Line 9:         System.out.println("You entered: " + number);
        Prints the converted number.

Line 10:        System.out.println("Number + 5 = " + (number + 5));
        Performs arithmetic after conversion.

Line 12:        sc.close();
        Closes the scanner to free resources.

Output (example):
Enter a number:
25
You entered: 25
Number + 5 = 30

Summary:
This program shows how parseInt() is useful when user input is taken as text but must be used as a number.

